Section 1: Data Ingestion & Missing Values


Objective: Identify and handle missing values at the data ingestion level


Data Loading


Dataset: AAVAIL Customer Activity


- Source: `aavail_customer_activity.csv`

- Records: 1,000 customers

- Markets: United States & Singapore

- Key Variables:

  • Customer demographics (age, country)
  • Subscription status (is_subscriber, subscriber_type)
  • Engagement metrics (num_streams)

customer_id country_name age customer_name is_subscriber subscriber_type num_streams
0 1 united_states 21.0 Kasen Todd True aavail_premium 23.0
1 2 singapore 31.0 Ensley Garza False NaN 12.0
2 3 united_states 22.0 Lillian Carey False aavail_premium 22.0
3 4 united_states 21.0 Beau Christensen True aavail_basic 19.0
4 5 singapore 22.0 Ernesto Gibson True aavail_premium 23.0

Missing Value Identification


Critical Step: Identify missing values immediately upon data ingestion


  • Missing values detected in:
  • `subscriber_type`: 72 missing (7.2%)
  • `num_streams`: 46 missing (4.6%)

- Impact: Missing subscriber_type is problematic as it's a key business metric


Imputation Strategy


Approach: Handle missing values systematically


1. `num_streams` (Numeric):

  • Method: Median imputation
  • Rationale: Robust to outliers
  • Value: 19.0 streams

2. `subscriber_type` (Categorical):

  • Method: Mode imputation
  • Rationale: Standard for categorical data
  • Value: 'aavail_basic' (most frequent plan)

Before vs After Imputation


Visual Comparison: Distribution changes after imputation


  • Shows impact of imputation on data distribution
  • Validates that imputation maintains data integrity

Columns Dropped


Data Cleaning Decision:


- Dropped: `customer_name`

- Rationale: Not needed for analysis, contains PII

- Impact: No loss of analytical value


Final Dataset: 7 columns retained for analysis


Section 2: Data Summary & Visualizations


Objective: Provide comprehensive visual summaries of the data


Dataset Overview


Key Statistics:


- Total Records: 1,000 customers

- Markets: 2 (United States: 700, Singapore: 300)

- Subscriber Types: 3 plans (basic, premium, unlimited)

- Age Range: 14-57 years (median: 24)

- Streams Range: 1-29 streams (median: 19)


Subscriber Type Distribution


Description: Distribution of subscription plans across both markets


  • Premium plan is most popular in both markets
  • Basic plan is second most common
  • Unlimited plan has smallest customer base

Streaming Activity Distribution


Description: Number of streams by subscription plan


  • Similar streaming patterns across all plans
  • No significant difference between basic and unlimited plans
  • Median streams: ~19 across all tiers

Age Demographics


Description: Customer age distribution by country


  • Core demographic: 19-35 age group
  • Similar patterns across US and Singapore
  • Consistent global user base profile

Section 3: Singapore Market Investigation


Objective: Identify factors explaining the Singapore market situation


Market Size Comparison


Key Finding:


- US Market: 700 customers (70%)

- Singapore Market: 300 customers (30%)


Implication: Singapore is a smaller but significant market segment


Factor 1: Plan Popularity Patterns


Description: Subscriber type distribution comparison


Singapore Findings:

  • Premium plan dominance (similar to US)
  • Basic plan as second choice
  • Unlimited plan underperforms

Interpretation: Singapore shows similar plan preferences to US market


Factor 2: Streaming Behavior


Description: Streaming activity patterns in Singapore


Critical Finding:

  • Unlimited plan shows LOWER median streams than basic/premium
  • All plans have similar streaming distributions
  • Singapore unlimited plan has outlier (near 0 streams)

Interpretation: Unlimited plan not delivering expected value in Singapore


Factor 3: Subscriber Conversion Rates


Description: Conversion from non-subscriber to subscriber status


Singapore Findings:

  • High conversion rate (similar to US)
  • Subscribers significantly outnumber non-subscribers
  • Effective platform conversion

Interpretation: Singapore market shows strong engagement


Factor 4: Age Demographics


Description: Age distribution patterns in Singapore


Singapore Findings:

  • Similar age distribution to US (median ~24-30)
  • Core demographic: 19-35 age group
  • Some older outliers (up to 70s) in basic/premium plans

Interpretation: Consistent global demographic profile


Factor 5: Churn Analysis


Description: Customer churn patterns in Singapore market


Key Metrics:

  • Overall churn rate by market
  • Churn by subscription plan
  • Relationship between streaming activity and churn

Interpretation: Identifies at-risk customer segments


Singapore Situation Summary


Key Factors Explaining Singapore Market:


1. Similar Plan Preferences: Premium plan dominance mirrors US


2. Unlimited Plan Underperformance: Lower streaming than basic/premium


3. Strong Conversion: High subscriber rates indicate effective platform


4. Consistent Demographics: Age patterns align with global profile


5. Market Size: Smaller but engaged customer base (30% of total)


Section 4: Results & Recommendations


Objective: Discuss findings and provide actionable recommendations


Key Findings


1. Missing Data Handled: 118 missing values imputed (7.2% subscriber_type, 4.6% num_streams)


2. Plan Performance: Premium most popular; unlimited underperforms in both markets


3. Streaming Patterns: No significant difference between plan tiers


4. Singapore Market: Shows similar patterns to US with smaller scale


5. Demographics: Consistent 19-35 age group across markets


Discussion of Results


Data Quality:

  • Systematic imputation maintained data integrity
  • Missing subscriber_type requires investigation at source

Business Insights:

  • Unlimited plan not delivering perceived value
  • Premium plan resonates with customers
  • Singapore market shows strong potential despite smaller size

Market Comparison:

  • Similar patterns suggest consistent global strategy possible
  • Singapore requires targeted approach for growth

Recommendations for AAVAIL


1. Re-evaluate Unlimited Plan

  • Conduct user research to understand value proposition
  • Consider repackaging with distinct features
  • Evaluate phasing out if not viable

2. Singapore Market Strategy

  • Focus on premium plan marketing
  • Investigate unlimited plan underperformance
  • Develop market-specific growth initiatives

3. Data Quality Improvements

  • Investigate source of missing subscriber_type data
  • Implement data validation at ingestion
  • Establish monitoring for data completeness

4. Marketing & Pricing

  • Continue premium plan promotion
  • Develop upsell campaigns (basic → premium)
  • Simplify offering if unlimited plan removed

Next Steps


Immediate Actions:

1. User research on unlimited plan subscribers

2. Data quality audit at source systems

3. Singapore market growth strategy development


Future Analysis:

  • Longitudinal churn analysis
  • Feature usage by plan type
  • Market expansion opportunities

Appendix: Technical Details


Methodology & Supplemental Information


Imputation Methodology


Numeric Variables (`num_streams`):

  • Method: Median imputation
  • Rationale: Robust to outliers
  • Imputed: 46 values with median 19.0

Categorical Variables (`subscriber_type`):

  • Method: Mode imputation
  • Rationale: Standard for categorical data
  • Imputed: 72 values with mode 'aavail_basic'

Data Dictionary


Key Variables:

  • `customer_id`: Unique identifier
  • `country_name`: Market (united_states, singapore)
  • `age`: Customer age in years
  • `is_subscriber`: Boolean subscription status
  • `subscriber_type`: Plan type (aavail_basic, aavail_premium, aavail_unlimited)
  • `num_streams`: Number of streams (engagement metric)

See: `docs/DATA_DICTIONARY.md` for complete documentation
